        url: "https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesbusinesscouncil/2022/05/10/into-the-metaverse-considerations-companies-should-keep-in-mind/",
        title:
          "Council Post: Into The Metaverse: Considerations Companies Should Keep In Mind",
        body: "Expertise from Forbes Councils members, operated under license. Opinions expressed are those of the author.\n\nTariq Akbar, CEO of LegalEase, helps lawyers use technology and outsourcing to improve organizational performance.\n\nThe growing popularity of nonfungible tokens (NFTs) and digital asset transactions, like virtual real estate, signals a growing legitimization of metaverse-based transactions and ecosystems. The metaverse, potentially an $800 billion market, entails complex, environment-specific rules that developers must consider as they assess the best ways to standardize these environments into the proposed Web 3.0 infrastructure.\n\nWith the addition of live events and social ads, this market can potentially double. Businesses need to be mindful of numerous considerations when building their metaverse initiatives to ensure their programs are managed within the company's risk frameworks.\n\nPrivacy\n\nThe metaverse can pose greater privacy risks than current social media platforms. Whether you're playing around in Sandbox or exchanging ADA for Pavia land plots, metaverse environment owners record your purchases on third-party blockchains or databases.\n\nWhile blockchain offers the asset protection of a decentralized system, individually-identifiable information can be gleaned from public blockchain records. Meta's Oculus headsets, for example, save a rolling buffer of your interactions with users in Horizon Worlds that Meta employees can tap into when investigating complaints.\n\nCopyright Issues\n\nIP issues can naturally be at play in a cross-border environment such as the metaverse. Cybercriminals can potentially create digital twins of assets and, without underlying blockchain tech to protect them, exploit these assets.\n\nNFT stores are growing exponentially, and copyright infringement is hard to track and identify. Coach recently pursued a pop-up shop version of this retail concept, albeit legally, with The Walt Disney Company and Keith Haring. Since the identities of plot owners in blockchain-based lands are anonymized, IP owners could struggle to hold infringers accountable. Often, the severest of penalties typically involve having the foundation or DAO (decentralized autonomous organization) in charge block user access to the platform.\n\nOnline Dispute Resolution Obstacles\n\nMany metaverse environments are in growth mode and are more focused on building their user bases and gaining traction than resolving user-to-user disputes. Should a user-to-user conflict arise, parties also have no centralized framework, judicial system or avenue to pursue resolution. Jurisdiction, especially in the metaverse, can be easy to hide and validate because of anonymity issues due to the level of transaction masking made possible by blockchain-based ledgers.\n\nUntil there is a centralized online regulatory authority and jurisdictional framework to govern metaverse-related disputes, companies and authorities must assess how to best implement rules and restrictions.\n\nUnstable, Speculation-Driven Metaverse Economies\n\nMany blockchain-driven metaverse economies rely on cryptocurrency usage. Decentraland users will likely compile LAND tokens, while Sandbox users will do the same with SAND. While cryptocurrencies and decentralized tokens have their perks -- anonymity, the absence of a centralized authority, transaction masking and the like -- they are still speculative investments that major government institutions do not back.\n\nAs a result, unpredictable near-term fluctuations in cryptocurrency demand and supply can disrupt the stability of metaverse-centered economies and undermine NFT-based real estate mortgages and asset class purchase values in the short term. As cryptocurrencies start to stabilize over the long term, some of this may change.\n\nSo, how can companies mitigate their liability for metaverse-related activities?\n\nFocus\n\nTo start, companies should form a metaverse-focused task force responsible for developing self-governing ethical, metaverse-centered frameworks. These teams should select focus groups within their respective organizations to assess the viability and evolutionary potential of those standards. Chief risk officers and chief legal officers can be ideal voices to rely on for such matters. Participants in other ethics-driven professions, including chief medical officers, can also offer unique insights.\n\nRisk Frameworks\n\nYour finalized frameworks and focus group input should help your organization structure pertinent team-wide training measures. Many underestimate the amount of education and knowledge required to fully grasp how the metaverse works and how transactions in these environments should operate, including the ethical issues that can evolve from collecting and handling biometric data, AR advertising and the like.\n\nMetaverse-focused teams, therefore, should ensure that employees have access to robust modules, online document repositories and tutorials with in-house and outside experts. Transaction management and monitoring, along with R&D initiatives, will also play a key role in helping your company adapt to dynamic metaverse developments. As the metaverse continues to evolve at a fast clip, organizations must develop frameworks or secure strategic partnerships to report on market developments and maximize the value of their metaverse transactions and activities.\n\nTraining\n\nCompanies must plan and implement substantial training to make sure their metaverse activities do not facilitate risk. While organizations will likely need to push for unified regulatory standards with the DAOs, foundations and for-profit companies engaging in the space, there are still steps that companies can pursue internally to mitigate their risks.\n\nThe metaverse holds great potential and opportunity for companies, so long as they approach it with the right planning and risk management. By focusing on risk frameworks, ethics and education, businesses can better navigate the moving targets within the metaverse.\n\nForbes Business Council is the foremost growth and networking organization for business owners and leaders. Do I qualify?",
