        dataType: "news",
        sim: 0,
        url: "https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesbusinesscouncil/2022/05/10/the-keys-to-unlocking-a-new-world-of-work/",
        title: "Council Post: The Keys To Unlocking A New World Of Work",
        body: "The Covid-19 pandemic provoked a profound societal reorganization affecting the way we work and live. Overnight, everyday activities we took for granted ceased and the labor market was upturned. The forced surge in remote working across the globe -- with 48% of workers in Europe working remotely at least part of the time during the early stages of the pandemic -- has brought about many changes. Workers are reevaluating the role that work plays in their lives and questioning whether a more flexible approach or reduced working hours may suit them better.\n\nAs the acute phase of the pandemic becomes a distant memory, workplaces are beginning the process of returning to normal. However, that normal is irrevocably changed. This new normal has spurred a conversation on what we want the labor market to look like and the overall state of workers' rights, including whether we need a four-day workweek and remote or hybrid work.\n\nThere has been a profound change in our relationship with work; we must seize the opportunity to build a new work world founded on the principles of social protection and well-being.\n\nTo make that happen, here are three key considerations to getting it right.\n\n1. Flexible work is here to stay, but it's not everyone's priority.\n\nFlexible work is now here to stay and the available talent landscape has fundamentally shifted, with a McKinsey study showing that \"[m]ore than 20 percent of the workforce could work remotely three to five days a week as effectively as they could if working from an office.\"\n\nThis means that the talent pool available to companies has increased, but it also means that workers can now easily apply for a wide array of opportunities and identify those that best match their needs.\n\nYet, workers do not want flexibility at all costs. They value the protection and safeguarding of their rights. Recognizing this, the EU is increasingly framing itself as a leader in regulatory development. In 2021, the EU proposed measures that would regulate platform work and minimize the chances for workers to fall through the cracks. Digital platforms operating from the U.S. have argued against the scope of these proposals, indicating that their business models may crumble if these regulations are enforced.\n\nIn the long run, U.S.-based businesses may need to adjust their business models significantly in the EU and ward off similar regulations in the U.S.\n\n2. The labor market must be re-humanized if we are to truly overcome its structural flaws.\n\nWith 41% of the global workforce considering leaving their employers within the next year and 69% of employers reporting difficulties in hiring, I believe the increasingly stark mismatch between employers' and job seekers' expectations is a major factor in what has been dubbed the Great Resignation. This phenomenon has swept both the EU and the U.S., with workers seeking more flexibility and opportunities that better match their needs.\n\nIt is critically important that skill shortages be addressed and the process of matching workers and employers be made as easy and efficient as possible. While this is undoubtedly a challenge, it also presents an opportunity to re-humanize the labor market and address the driving factors of what should have been called the Great Mismatch rather than the Great Resignation.\n\nWhile the pandemic reinforced the desire for more flexibility in some regions, it has highlighted the inherent vulnerabilities of many workers in other parts of the world. It is estimated that over 60% of all workers worldwide work in the informal economy and are thus unable to avail themselves of their full rights. We must look to develop and provide the necessary layer of protection for those at risk of forced and bonded labor. By acting responsibly and upholding ethical standards, a safe pathway to employment can be ensured.\n\nFrom social protection to support schemes, there are many experts and tools offering innovative and dynamic solutions to help overcome problems affecting the workforce. These include digital solutions such as blockchain and artificial intelligence.\n\n3. Learning doesn't end in school; workers have a lifelong right to training and access to new opportunities.\n\nStudies have shown that during periods with tight employment markets, such as the one we are currently experiencing, employers de-emphasize degrees and focus instead on demonstrated skills and competencies. This is a perfect opportunity for workers to make use of training and reskilling programs to transition into new roles and industries.\n\nDuring the pandemic, the private employment industry helped address glaring gaps in the workforce by training and placing workers operating in essential sectors such as healthcare and the construction industry. Agency workers in many countries have taken advantage of training opportunities, with the highest percentages appearing in Japan (100%), the U.S. (84%), Canada (84%) and Mexico (58%).\n\nCareer management has also been in high demand during the pandemic. Expert advisors offered vital support to companies that needed to restructure and to workers who required guidance to land new opportunities during periods of transformation and uncertainty.\n\nFinal Thoughts\n\nThe Covid-19 pandemic has impacted every person across the globe and changed society forever. It has led to talent shortages, more demand for flexible work and better consideration for work-life balance.\n\nCultivating a workplace culture that ensures training and internal talent mobility can help organizations thrive. Career management firms especially can play a supportive role for organizations. Moreover, by incorporating learning management systems, businesses can stimulate a long-term learning culture and renew investment and interest from leaders and managers. Data show that 80% of HR leaders believe that increased talent mobility leads to significant benefits including higher retention, greater career satisfaction and better culture fit.\n\nWe must work toward the development of a fair and resilient labor market for every worker across the world and ensure that today's challenges are a distant memory in tomorrow's workplace.\n\nForbes Business Council is the foremost growth and networking organization for business owners and leaders. Do I qualify?",
