        url: "https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesbusinesscouncil/2022/05/10/five-myths-about-the-death-of-retail/",
        title: "Council Post: Five Myths About The Death Of Retail",
        body: "Expertise from Forbes Councils members, operated under license. Opinions expressed are those of the author.\n\nCo-Founder and CEO of Zipline, a company that helps brick-and-mortar stores streamline communication and task management.\n\nIt's fashionable these days to pronounce the death of the physical world. The tech press reads like an obituary page -- gold killed by Bitcoin, the office killed by Zoom, reality itself killed by the metaverse. Unsurprisingly, perhaps, many believe the rise of Amazon and a host of wildly popular direct-to-consumer (D2C) brands has spelled the end of retail, too. The narrative is infectious and the prognosis is inevitably bleak. But when it comes to retail, it couldn't be further from the truth.\n\nIt's not hard to see how this idea took hold. Walk around any major downtown area from San Francisco to New York and you'll find plenty of shuttered storefronts with signs in the window thanking loyal customers for years of business. Many people assume this is the fallout from D2C competition or savvy businesses moving online to save themselves. While this is undoubtedly part of the explanation, it's hardly the full picture.\n\nThe fact is that retail is a dynamic sector that is going through major changes that require stores to stay agile to survive. But is retail dead? Hardly. When we examine some of the most pernicious myths about the future of retail, we find that they quickly fall apart under scrutiny.\n\nMyth 1: D2C will cannibalize brick-and-mortar stores.\n\nWho hasn't seen someone at the office wearing a fresh pair of kicks from Allbirds, which managed to make a shoe that was both extremely comfortable and environmentally benign? Ask someone where they got their glasses and there's a good chance they'll tell you Warby Parker, which has made fashionable and affordable eyewear available to everyone. Need a new mattress? Casper will ship it in a box to your doorstep. [Full disclosure: Allbirds and Warby Parker are Zipline customers.]\n\nBesides a knack for elevated consumer products, these online brands have something in common: As they became successful, they all opened physical stores because they understood the value that storefronts bring to a brand. They afford customers the opportunity to admire and try out their products before buying them, becoming a destination online and in real life.\n\nMyth 2: E-commerce meets all of a consumer's needs.\n\nThere's no doubt that ecommerce has removed friction from the shopping experience. With one click, we can go from thinking about an item to summoning it to our doorstep. But ease and efficiency represent only a small part of the shopping experience -- and may not even be the most important one.\n\nModern consumers expect brands to lead a hybrid existence that straddles the digital and physical divide just as they themselves do. The majority of shoppers will conduct an online search before they visit a physical store and, as a result, brands with an omnichannel strategy will see greater customer retention rates compared to businesses that are purely digital or purely analog. This desire for an in-person shopping experience is so strong that many consumers even prefer to return the goods they bought online to a physical store rather than shipping them back to the company.\n\nMyth 3: Retail is a low-skill job.\n\nThere is an unfounded belief that retail sales are a low-skill job. Automation may be more popular now, but there's no replacing human interaction.\n\nThe truth is that retail sales is a complex job that requires not only a healthy dose of intelligence but a strong helping of interpersonal skills, too. Retail salespeople must manage inventory, shop operations, marketing, customer relations and many other duties that will be incredibly challenging to replace with AI or robots for the foreseeable future. Most importantly, they provide a personal experience that customers will always crave, whether it's a product recommendation or simply a smile when they come into the store.\n\nMyth 4: Retailers can achieve faster growth online.\n\nOne of the main pillars of the death of retail myth is the notion that brick-and-mortar stores simply can't compete with digital-first brands. The problem is that this simply doesn't reflect the way these businesses are actually run.\n\nAlthough starting a D2C brand may require less capital upfront compared to a physical store, sustaining an online brand is incredibly challenging. It's expensive to acquire customers and the chances of converting a visitor to a brand's website into a customer hover below 3%.\n\nThe same is not true for physical stores. Not only are customers more likely to buy a product once they're in the store, they also tend to spend more. This leads to steady, predictable growth that can last for years or decades. The growth of D2C brands may look like they're riding a rocketship when they first start, but all too often this growth turns out to be unsustainable and the next big thing becomes just another flash in the pan.\n\nMyth 5: Stores are only for selling products.\n\nWhen you visit a website of your favorite brand, you might find a blog or another form of lighthearted content, but for the most part, the website exists to funnel you into a purchase. Chances are there is a big \"buy now\" button front and center on the home page. These sites are ruthlessly optimized to convert visitors at all costs, and there is a tendency to project these tactics onto brick-and-mortar stores as well. But physical retailers offer so much more.\n\nWalk into a store and you will encounter an ambiance, not a sales funnel. There is music, evolving displays and, most importantly, other people. The community-driven aspect of physical retail locations is their most enduring quality. In addition to selling products, they bring people together through events, whether its yoga sessions at Lululemon or a rock wall at REI. [Full disclosure: Lululemon is a customer of Zipline.] They spark conversations between customers and employees. They offer so much more than the products that line their shelves.\n\nMake no mistake: Physical retail stores are evolving rapidly. But to paraphrase the great Mark Twain, reports of their death have been greatly exaggerated.\n\nForbes Business Council is the foremost growth and networking organization for business owners and leaders. Do I qualify?",
