        url: "https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesbusinesscouncil/2022/05/09/solving-the-plastics-problem-demands-systems-thinking/",
        title:
          "Council Post: Solving The Plastics Problem Demands Systems Thinking",
        body: 'Expertise from Forbes Councils members, operated under license. Opinions expressed are those of the author.\n\nDr. Steen Tjarks is the President and Co-Founder at T&T Design, a global packaging and artwork agency that specilaizes in private label.\n\nThere are 500 times more microplastics in our oceans than stars in our galaxy. This is partially caused by the breakdown of larger plastic debris, including packaging. Thanks to increasing regulation and shifting public opinion, change is under way, but our efforts need to be unified. To make a real difference, we need to adopt the approach American scientist Peter Senge calls systems thinking, "a discipline for seeing the structures that underlie complex situations, and for discerning high from low leverage change."\n\nThinking Outside The Box\n\nToday, companies talk about the circular economy, a cradle-to-cradle concept that rethinks what enters the market and keeps it in the loop thereafter. Environmental, Social and Governance (ESG) funds are on track to reach $53 trillion by 2025 and even U.S. businesses, which have, to date, lagged behind in issues of sustainability, have issued an inspiring new statement on the purpose of American corporations that pledges "shared prosperity and sustainability for both business and society."\n\nBut, apart from a few high-profile initiatives from companies like Starbucks and Coca-Cola, is the corporate world doing enough to tackle the problem of plastic packaging? A 2020 packaging sustainability report from McKinsey claims that historically, companies have pursued a limited packaging sustainability agenda, focused on "quick wins" like reducing weight and material usage improvements. The same report asserts that Fast-Moving Consumer Goods (FMGC) companies and retailers "will require much closer collaboration with upstream players, packaging converters, and recyclers" to instigate real change. The report calls for deep scientific research into plastic substitutes and the creation of circular value chains, and highlights the need to educate consumers.\n\nUpstream: Recycling Connectivity\n\nThere is evidence that some influential, world-leading brands are moving in the right direction. In pursuit of a vertical integration strategy, Ikea invested in a plastic recycling plant to help attain its goal of producing 100% circular products by 2030.\n\nHowever, vertical integration can go further, such as sourcing recycled raw material from the plastic that is currently destroying our ecosystem. In the Asia-Pacific region alone, there are around 11.1 billion plastic items entangled on coral reefs, a figure that is expected to jump 40% by 2025. The FMCG manufacturers and retailers that are responsible for the bulk of plastic packaging can go further by taking a deeper, more ecological approach that emphasizes restorative action. This extension to environmental stewardship might mean corporate sponsorships of NGOs focused on coral restoration or investments in man-made coral reefs that are powered by wave, wind or solar energy.\n\nMidstream: Design And Materials Innovation\n\nA 2020 report called "Breaking the Plastic Wave" says that current commitments by corporations and governments are inadequate for the scale of the plastic challenge. So what else can be done and how can the design industry help?\n\nBecause of the many colors in which plastics are produced, recycled plastic is usually monochrome, unattractive for branding purposes. Consumers may declare that gray packs are preferable to dirty oceans, yet their subconscious expectations speak as loudly as brand owners\' desire to appeal and differentiate. Evian launched its first bottle made of recycled plastic to much acclaim, featuring an embossed logo instead of a label. However, a preferable solution, according to Prof. Edward Kosior, would be to facilitate mixed recycling by focusing design cues on labels (with self-peeling or dissolvable glue) and stretch-sleeves. Packaging designers must work closely with brand owners, taking full responsibility for every facet of packaging. They must also collaborate with material scientists, finding ways to replace traditional plastics with algae-based bioplastics, paper, bamboo and mushroom styrofoam. Rather than just responding to client briefs, design agencies should make it their business to understand sustainability issues and lead the way.\n\nDownstream: Consumer Engagement\n\nIncreasingly, packaging contains data that enables traceability down the supply chain, supported by blockchain technology. It records the provenance of the product and vouches for its sustainability credentials, from human rights to environmental performance. This data could potentially track the origins of the pack itself, proving where, how and when it was made or recycled and what will happen to it after consumption. Using QR or AR codes on packaging, consumers are now able to use their mobile phones as a personal lens to enter a new dimension, the interactive world of Virtual, Augmented and Mixed Reality, in which the backstory of the combined product and pack can be shared.\n\nThe pack can also exert influence on the forward story. Food packaging specialist Huhtamaki recently launched an initiative to increase cup recycling, including using QR codes to redirect users to a landing page containing details of the growing numbers of cup recycling sites and schemes. QR codes might be a powerful tool to educate consumers about packaging in general as well as how to dispose of the packaging they\'re currently using.\n\nA 360-Degree Mindset\n\nAlbert Einstein famously stated that we cannot solve problems by using the same kind of thinking we used to create them. The World Wildlife Foundation recently brought together multiple companies to address the plastic issue through a new activation hub. Representatives of these companies are clearly aware of the scope of the problem, citing the need for collective action and "unprecedented levels of ambition and collaboration."\n\nContrary to some skeptics who believe that big business will hijack the sustainability agenda for its own ends, I find it more likely that we will witness a new form of what John Fullerton in 2015 called "regenerative capitalism," that will "turn today\'s lopsided (and unsustainable) form of capitalism into an integrated network of balanced, vibrant, and regenerative economies, all serving systemic health within their own unique contexts." Achieving that vision demands interconnectivity, collective thinking throughout the entire supply chain. Manufacturers, retailers, recyclers, material scientists, environmentalists, packaging designers and the consumer all have a part to play. If the stars align, there\'s every chance that they will once again outnumber the microplastics in our oceans.\n\nForbes Business Council is the foremost growth and networking organization for business owners and leaders. Do I qualify?',
