        url: "https://www.marketwatch.com/articles/gold-prices-inflation-etfs-51651854884",
        title:
          "Gold Rises as Investors Seeking an Inflation Haven Pour Into Gold ETFs",
        body: "Gold didn't get the message that higher interest rates mean lower prices for the yellow metal.\n\nThe Federal Reserve raised rates by a widely expected 50 basis points (a half-percentage point) on Wednesday, signaling a series of rate hikes this year and a plan to reduce its balance sheet. Although gold slipped immediately after the Fed's move, prices resumed their climb on Thursday, and gold-market watchers say the metal still has more mettle in it.\n\nNormally, gold is less desirable to own when rates rise because it has no yield, making other yield-bearing havens like bonds more attractive. Yet there's a nuance to this narrative. What matters for gold are \"real\" interest rates -- those calculated by subtracting the inflation rate from the nominal rate. The federal-funds rate is now 0.75% to 1%, but the March consumer price index put inflation at 8.5%, so real rates remain well in negative territory.\n\nWill Rhind, chief executive of GraniteShares, issuer of the $1 billion GraniteShares Gold Trust exchange-traded fund (ticker: BAR), says that gold has an advantage over cash and bonds if nominal interest rates are positive but the real rates remain negative, since gold isn't losing value.\n\nJust as important as real interest rates is the trend and pace of the Fed's rate hikes. The gold market had priced in a 50-basis-point hike on Wednesday, Rhind says, which is why prices slipped modestly then and rebounded on Thursday. Gold actually made a new high for the week on Thursday, rising above $1,900 an ounce.\n\nRelated Market Data\n\nThat's still about $180 below February's all-time nominal high around $2,080, spurred by high inflation and Russia's invasion of Ukraine. Since then, prices have deteriorated. They were about $1,850 as of Tuesday, as traders removed some of the war premium and in anticipation of the Fed's move.\n\nFed Chairman Jerome Powell signaled that \"50 basis-point increases should be on the table at the next couple of meetings\" of the Federal Open Market Committee, but that pace of increases isn't hawkish enough to pressure gold significantly, says Adrian Day, CEO of Adrian Day Asset Management, which specializes in resource investing. In his postmeeting press conference, Powell shot down the option for 75-basis-point hikes in the near term.\n\nBased on the central bank chief's post-FOMC comments, TD Securities expects that the Federal Reserve will continue to ratchet up rates until fed funds reach the 3% to 3.25% target range by March 2023. Even if nominal rates jump to about 3.25%, they'd still be significantly below the real rate, Day says.\n\n\"The most aggressive projections of Fed actions over the next 12 months will get the Fed to about 3.4%. Inflation is at 8.5%. At the end of this so-called hawkish Fed's first year of tightening...we will be more deeply negative in real terms than we were in 1975-76, at the beginning of the great inflation of the 1970s,\" Day says.\n\nInflation HavenInvestment flows from exchange-traded gold funds have played a key role in driving up gold prices. Fund / TickerAUM (bil)YTD Total Return 1-Yr Total Return 3-Yr Total Return SPDR Gold Trust / GLD$65.22.8%5.5%13.4%iShares Gold Trust / IAU31.22.95.713.6SPDR Gold MiniShares Trust / GLDM5.33.05.813.6abrdn Physical Gold Shares / SGOL2.73.05.813.7iShares Gold Trust Micro / IAUM1.22.8N/AN/AGraniteShares Gold Trust / BAR1.03.05.813.6\n\nNote: Returns through May 4. Three-year returns are annualized. N/A=not applicable\n\nSource: Morningstar\n\nIn March, the Fed forecast that 2022 median core personal consumption expenditures -- its go-to inflation measure -- would be at 4.1% and saw the PCE in 2023 at 2.6%. The latest monthly core PCE reading in March was 5.2%.\n\n\"The Fed is thinking that inflation is going to be barely 4% by the end of the year. I think they're living in cloud-cuckoo land,\" Day observes.\n\nInvestment demand for gold might remain strong if real interest rates stay negative. That demand rose significantly in the first quarter of 2022, versus its level in the same period last year, according to the World Gold Council, an industry group.\n\nIn its first-quarter Gold Demand Trends publication, the group said that global investment demand, which includes that linked to ETFs, physical gold bars, and coins, rose 203% in the quarter, to 551 metric tons, versus 182 metric tons during the same period in 2021. The gain was led by ETF demand, up 269 metric tons versus an outflow in 2021's first quarter. This was the highest level of quarterly flows since 2020's third quarter.\n\nGold faces some headwinds in the near term, with the World Gold Council noting that the total supply jumped in the first quarter. Mine production rose 3%, year over year, to a record level, and supply-recycled gold, which is already-mined metal that's sold for scrap, increased 15%. Jewelry demand fell 7%, as consumers in China and India, the two top global purchasers of gold earrings, necklaces, and other baubles, acquired less. Central bank purchases were also muted in the quarter, down 29% versus the total a year earlier.\n\nBoth the slump in jewelry demand and increase in supply, especially scrap gold, are reactions to the first quarter's high prices, Rhind says. Persistent high prices could temper jewelry demand, but investment demand is the category to watch. Jewelry demand and mine supply tend to be correlated to global economic growth, but investment demand, particularly from ETFs, has more price impact than these other drivers, he adds.\n\nThe Fed's actions and their impact on real interest rates is the overarching influence on gold prices. But what's also critical are market perceptions of how well the Federal Reserve is balancing the battle against inflation and whether it's engineering a soft economic landing to avoid a recession. Rhind recalls that gold's 1970s inflation-induced parabolic rally took some time.\n\n\"It wasn't until the last couple of years that things started to get out of control. I think people felt like the central bank had lost control, and then the gold price really skyrocketed,\" he says.\n\nBoth Day and Rhind suggest that gold could return to its nominal all-time high, hit in February. Some forecasters look for the metal to reach $3,000 an ounce in two years. However, even that lofty price wouldn't top gold's January 1980 peak of $875, in inflation-adjusted terms. To do that, the metal would have to rise to a little over $3,200 an ounce, according to the CPI inflation calculator.\n\nEmail:",
